Name: Midnight Mass
Review:
‚ÄúWhat happens when you die? Speaking for yourself.‚Äù

‚ÄúMyself. My self. That‚Äôs the problem. That‚Äôs the whole problem with the whole thing. That word, ‚Äúself.‚Äù Thats not the word. That‚Äôs not right, that isn‚Äôt‚Ä¶How did I forget that? When did I forget that? The body stops a cell at a time, but the brain keeps firing those neurons. Little lightning bolts, like fireworks inside and I thought I‚Äôd despair or feel afraid, but I don‚Äôt feel any of that. None of it. Because I‚Äôm too busy. I‚Äôm too busy in the moment. Remembering. Of course. I remember that every atom in my body was forged in a star. This matter, this body is mostly empty space after all, and solid matter. It‚Äôs just energy vibrating very slowly while there is no me. There never was. The electrons of my body mingle and dance with the electrons of the ground below me and the air I‚Äôm no longer breathing. And I remember there is no point where any of that ends and I begin. I remember I am energy. Not memory. Not self. My name, my personality, my choices, all came after me. I was before them and I will be after, and everything else is pictures, picked up along the way. Fleeting little dreamlets printed on the tissue of my dying brain. And I am the lightning that jumps between. I am the energy firing the neurons, and I‚Äôm returning. Just by remembering, I‚Äôm returning home. And it‚Äôs like a drop of water falling back into the ocean, of which it‚Äôs always been a part. All things‚Ä¶ a part. You, me and my little girl, and my mother and my father, everyone who‚Äôs ever been, every plant, every animal, every atom, every start, every galaxy, all of it. More galaxies in the universe than grains of sand on the beach. And that‚Äôs what we‚Äôre talking about when we say ‚ÄúGod.‚Äù The cosmos and its infinite dreams. We are the cosmos dreaming of itself. It‚Äôs simply a dream that I think is my life, every time. But I‚Äôll forget this. I always do. I always forget my dreams. But now, in this split-second, in the moment I remember, the instant I remember, I comprehend everything at once. There is no time. There is no death. Life is a dream. It‚Äôs a wish. Made again and again and again and again and again and again and on into eternity. And I am all of it. I am everything. I am all. I am that I am.‚Äù

Name: Trap
Review:
Surprised this isn‚Äôt as well received by the majority. This movie did everything for me. Maybe I‚Äôm simple but this very much hit my emotions.¬†

A serial killer as a protagonist? How am I supposed to feel about him succeeding or even like him? (It helps that Josh Hartnett's hot hot crispy hot) Well the person we become familiar with is a loving dad, someone that the nervous system would signal is safe and for me, that worked‚Äîseeing him invested in his daughter and take joy in watching her grow and find confidence (even if it was by his attempts to escape).¬†

Seeing him later portray a cold and calculated killer was plenty of a rug pull (I knew it was coming so it was more of an emotional rug). The pop star, and the wife making their plays so intelligently was what carried the final act further than I am conditioned by Hollywood to expect (breaking that dumb scary movie trope of fear leading people to do the very wrong thing that leads to their death)

And the last thing that really sent it home for me was the contrast between the profiler‚Äôs final lines with that of the pop star‚Äôs attempt to lean into his mom‚Äôs power over him. Where the first attempt failed to connect ‚Äî‚Äúyou are not a monster‚Äù‚Äîwas in who he thinks he is. He believes he‚Äôs a monster. We cannot bear the pain of being bare and seen and rejected and in his case people were terrified and disgusted with who he is, striped down (literally shirtless hubba hubba), enter the hallucination of his mom telling him that she sees he's a monster and accepts him as that‚Äîall that anyone desperately wants is to be accepted when we are seen for what we believe we really are
